From: PS3 Custom Toolchain
Subject: [PATCH] elf64-ppc: tag Cell OS Lv-2 ELF headers on output

When the output ELF contains a .sys_proc_prx_param section — which
indicates it is a Cell OS Lv-2 userland binary — write the Cell OS
Lv-2 OS/ABI identifier (byte 0x66) into e_ident[EI_OSABI] and set
e_flags to exactly 0x01000000. Both values are required by the Lv-2
loader and are documented in docs/abi/cellos-lv2-abi-spec.md in the
PS3 Custom Toolchain tree.

Note that e_flags is assigned rather than OR'd: the Lv-2 ABI does
not use the EF_PPC64_ABI low bits that the ppc64 backend otherwise
sets to mark ELFv1 / ELFv2. Reference Lv-2 binaries carry
e_flags = 0x01000000 exactly.

Gating on the presence of .sys_proc_prx_param keeps standard ppc64
output (Linux, FreeBSD, bare-metal) unaffected — only PS3 userland
binaries, which uniquely ship that section, receive the tags.

--- a/bfd/elf64-ppc.c
+++ b/bfd/elf64-ppc.c
@@ -133,6 +133,7 @@
 #define elf_backend_section_flags	      ppc64_elf_section_flags
 #define elf_backend_merge_symbol_attribute    ppc64_elf_merge_symbol_attribute
 #define elf_backend_merge_symbol	      ppc64_elf_merge_symbol
+#define elf_backend_final_write_processing    ppc64_elf_final_write_processing
 #define elf_backend_get_reloc_section	      bfd_get_section_by_name

 /* The name of the dynamic interpreter.  This is put in the .interp
@@ -18407,6 +18408,25 @@
   return _bfd_elf_free_cached_info (abfd);
 }

+/* Tag Cell OS Lv-2 userland output with its OS/ABI identifier and
+   the e_flags value required by the Lv-2 loader. Detected by the
+   presence of .sys_proc_prx_param in the output — a section unique
+   to Lv-2 process parameter blocks — so standard ppc64 targets
+   (Linux, FreeBSD, bare-metal) are unaffected. e_flags is assigned
+   rather than OR'd because Lv-2 does not use the EF_PPC64_ABI low
+   bits that otherwise mark ELFv1 / ELFv2.  */
+
+static bool
+ppc64_elf_final_write_processing (bfd *abfd)
+{
+  if (bfd_get_section_by_name (abfd, ".sys_proc_prx_param") != NULL)
+    {
+      elf_elfheader (abfd)->e_ident[EI_OSABI] = 0x66;
+      elf_elfheader (abfd)->e_flags = 0x01000000;
+    }
+  return _bfd_elf_final_write_processing (abfd);
+}
+
 #include "elf64-target.h"

 /* FreeBSD support */
